{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488275"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:35:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:35:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"399"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/399"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.03,0.06,0.7,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61572"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/399"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47025"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"380"},{"type":"tags","id":"1216"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3870"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"10691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42074"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44458"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61572"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents with a two month history of an intermittent pain and numbness in her right hand. These symptoms would sometimes wake her at night. Her medical history includes rheumatoid arthritis and B12 deficiency. Her medications include methotrexate and once monthly B12 injections. She currently works at a court as a stenographer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination there is bilateral ulnar deviation of the metacarpophalangeal joints and swan-neck deformities of the fingers. Examination of the right wrist demonstrates signs of mild effusion. There is paraesthesia in the lateral three digits when full flexion is applied to her right wrist. Active and passive movements of her hands are mildly restricted, however, she is able to perform functional tasks such as writing with a pen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most responsible for her current symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid cervical spondylitis","Folate deficiency","B12 peripheral neuropathy","Carpal tunnel syndrome","Repetition strain injury"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is the clinical picture of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarpal tunnel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (CTS), which classically presents as tingling, numbness, or pain in the lateral three digits of the hand due to compression of the median nerve as it passes through the carpal tunnel. Women are at a higher risk of developing CTS, as are people who work in occupations requiring frequent and repetitive use of their hands or fingers. Other aetiology includes rheumatoid arthritis, hypothyroidism and pregnancy. This clinical presentation likely represents CTS secondary to rheumatoid arthritis. This can occur due to increased intracarpal pressure in the wrist, and synovial enlargement which causes compression of the median nerve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOften examination is normal, however the symptoms can sometimes be elicited with maintained 90\u00b0 flexion or extension of the wrist (Phalen\u2019s and reverse Phalen\u2019s test, respectively), or with percussion over the flexor retinaculum (Tinel\u2019s test).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepetitive strain injury (RSI) \u003C/strong\u003Ecan occur in multiple body sites and is caused by repetitive tasks, vibration and exertion. Symptoms can be similar to CTS with paraesthesia or loss of strength due to pain in the affected muscle or joint. The most common areas being the wrist, fingers, thumb and forearm where repetitive motion occurs, but does not follow a dermatome pattern as found in CTS, unless it affects the median nerve which his more specifically referred to as CTS. However, based on her history her symptoms are more likely to be aligned with CTS secondary to rheumatoid arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid arthritis can affect the cervical spine causing \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical spondylitis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EThis\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ewould cause symptoms such as neck pain and stiffness, headaches and symptoms relating to impingement of the spinal nerve root which follows a dermatomal and/or myotomal distribution, and would not be elicited using Phalen\u2019s test. Extension of the neck while turning towards the affected side and applying downwards pressure (Spurling\u2019s test) may elicit the pain caused by cervical spondylitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EB12 deficiency \u003C/strong\u003Ecan result in peripheral neuropathy resulting in proprioception and vibration loss, and foot drop. It can also present with symptoms of aneamia and glossitis. However the absence of theses symptoms and adequate management of her deficiency with B12 injections makes this option unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMethotrexate can reduce folate levels resulting in \u003Cstrong\u003Efolate deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E. Folate deficiency has overlapping symptoms with B12 deficiency as well as mouth ulcers, muscle weakness and fatigue. Peripheral neuropathy can be present in folate deficiency but it typically involves the lower extremities with a tendency to affect deep rather than superficial sensory loss, which is not present in this case and less likely to be related to her presentation of her paraesthesia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nocturnal paraesthesia in the fingers is a cardinal symptom of carpal tunnel syndrome.","Carpal tunnel syndrome can occur due to repetitive wrist use, and secondary to rheumatoid arthritis, hypothyroidism and pregnancy"],"references":["Thatte MR, Mansukhani KA. Compressive neuropathy in the upper limb. Indian J Plast Surg. 2011;44(2):283-297. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3193641/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47025"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"399"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47025"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-15T20:39:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-15T20:40:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"399"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61572"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"g